Date: Sat 21 May 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Statistics South Africa, 2002, Sat 21 May 2005 [edited]
<http://www.mrc.ac.za/researchreports/statssa.htm>

[The MRC Report discussed in the preceding reports is contained in the
document referred to below. Mod.CP]

Statistics South Africa - Causes of death in South Africa 1997-2001 -
Advance release of recorded causes of death
--------------------------------------------------
On 21 Nov 2002, Statistics South Africa released a report of the recorded
deaths in South Africa (pdf format 602 kb) (<http://www.statssa.gov.za/>
and <http://www.mrc.ac.za/researchreports/causesofdeath.pdf>) based on a 12
percent sample of death certificates for the period 1997-2001. The results
show a rapidly changing cause of death profile with increasing proportions
of TB, HIV and influenza and pneumonia deaths and decreasing proportions of
unnatural causes during this period. A Task Team including the Departments
of Health, Social Development, Home Affairs and the Medical Research
Council provided technical support in the planning and implementation of
the study.
In 2004 the MRC released a report in which it was estimated that about 25
percent of all deaths were due to HIV/AIDS. The Statistics South Africa
study finds a lower percentage (9 percent) of deaths recorded as being due
to HIV. A major reason for this difference is that these studies measure
different things.
The Statistics South Africa data reflect the information recorded on the
death certificates. In the absence of HIV status of all deceased, death
certificates will tend to reflect immediate cause of deaths or, in the case
of AIDS, the indicator conditions. The MRC approach, however, was to assess
the impact of HIV/AIDS as an underlying cause of death, based on the
observed excess mortality among young adults.
The MRC research team considers that the number of deaths attributable to
HIV is the leading cause of death and plans to undertake further analysis
of these valuable data as well as other data to refine the estimates of the
actual impact.
Dr Debbie Bradshaw (DPhil)
MRC Burden of Disease Research Unit
22 Nov 2002
